### **Aim** {#aim}

Let’sEat aims to be an all-in-one meal arrangement app that strengthens social connections by making eating with friends more convenient, spontaneous and stress-free.

### **Motivation** {#motivation}

Throughout our time at NUS, it is common to see canteens and cafes packed with students enjoying meals together. These shared meals are an integral part of campus life, fostering community and camaraderie. However, despite the bustling dining areas, many students can still be seen eating alone or opting for takeaways to avoid the discomfort of dining solo in public.

Mealtimes should be more than just a quick break in a busy schedule. They present a valuable and convenient opportunity for students to connect, whether by forming new friendships or rekindling old ones. Eating together can enhance the university experience by creating a sense of belonging and reducing feelings of loneliness.

### **Vision** {#vision}

Let’sEat will transform the way students at NUS connect over meals by allowing students to coordinate meals with others effortlessly – be it their friends, their faculty mates, or even nearby peers they wish to get to know better. These meals can be planned in advance or decided on-the-spot. While it may seem as simple as finding someone to have a meal with, our app will bring much convenience and simplicity to meal planning amid busy student lives. 

In the bigger scheme of things, we hope that our app can function as a vibrant social networking platform. By making it easier to share meals, Let'sEat will enable users to create and sustain meaningful relationships, fostering a stronger sense of community on campus. We hope that through these shared dining experiences, students will build lasting connections that enhance their university experience and beyond.

### **User Stories** {#user-stories}

1. As a user, I want to be able to add/remove friends in the app. 

2. As a user, I want to be able to see the profiles of nearby individuals and those within my social group (e.g. residence, faculty), so I can make informed decisions about who to invite for meals.

3. As a user, I want the option to send invitations to a friend, specific social groups or even to strangers who are also looking for meal buddies.

4. As a user who wants to find a meal buddy, I want to be able to alert my friends that I am available to eat, so they can join me if they are free.

5. As a user, I want to be able to set whether I am open to receiving requests from strangers.

6. As a user, I want to be able to know the common availabilities amongst my friends to book them for a meal in advance.

7. As a user, I want to be able to send requests to my friends to help me with takeaway food. Anyone who finds it convenient can accept it. 

8. As a user unfamiliar with the food options in school, I want to be able to see food recommendations based on my current location. 

### **Scope of Project** {#scope-of-project}

Let'sEat is a mobile application designed for the NUS community, facilitating meal coordination among its users. The platform fosters connections among individuals and friends, allowing them to organise meals either spontaneously or through pre-arranged bookings. Additionally, users can request assistance for takeaways from their friends. To enhance user experience, the application goes beyond connecting solely with friends; users can explore profiles of others who share similar characteristics, such as belonging to the same faculty or residing in the same hall. LetsEat’s features are outlined in the following sections.

### **Features** {#features}

#### **User Account Authentication**  {#user-account-authentication}

##### **Description** {#description}

As Let’sEat is a networking platform, each user will need to be authenticated with his/her own unique account. 

Utilising the Firebase SDK Authentication, users can:

* Log in via email and a password  
* Create an account if the user does not have an existing account  
* Reset password (a password reset email will be sent to the given email)

Based on the user’s action, the relevant call to the Firebase authentication instance is made. For instance, registering with email and password calls createUserWithEmailAndPassword, whereas logging into the app calls signInWithEmailAndPassword.

Upon successful account registration, users will be routed to the onboarding screens to set up their profile. After which, they will be routed back to log in to ensure they have completed their email verification.

Upon successful login in the future, users will be routed to the home page.

Behind the scenes, the necessary Firebase Authentication methods are invoked and any FirebaseAuthException(s) thrown are handled. Exceptions are converted to user-friendly messages and then returned to users through popups, alerting users of what had caused their login or sign-up to fail.

##### **Implementation Philosophy**  {#implementation-philosophy}

When users first open the mobile app, getReactNativePersistence(AsyncStorage) will first check if the user is logged in. If the user is logged in, he will be directed to the Home page. If the user is not logged in, he will have to login with a verified email and password, or create a new account. 

We have also implemented error handling for erroneous inputs for all the text input fields in the login and signup pages. No duplicate username or email is allowed.

##### **Implementation Challenges** {#implementation-challenges}

For user authentication, the key challenge was the routing of users to the relevant pages. After completing the signup page, users will be brought to the Homepage without having to verify their emails and will stay logged into the app (if they do not click on the log-out button). We decided to sign out the user after onboarding and route them to the login page to ensure their emails are verified before they can continue to use the app.

**Possible Extensions**  
Implement verification and security features upon account creation to ensure safety of users when arranging meals with strangers.

#### **Onboarding and Profile Creation** {#onboarding-and-profile-creation}

##### **Description** {#description-1}

After new users have successfully signed up, they will need to complete an onboarding process for the app to collect relevant information for their profile creation. The information provided by the user is broadly categorised into two categories: Basic Information and Additional Information:

Basic Information (for account personalisation): profile picture, bio  
Additional Information (to find users belonging to the same social groups): faculty, campus accommodation and preferred cuisines

Upon completing the signup and onboarding process, users' information will be updated in the Firebase Realtime Database.

Users will be able to edit their profile later on in the app, through the Profile page.

##### **Implementation philosophy**  {#implementation-philosophy-1}

Onboarding screens are created via react-native-onboarding-swiper package and react-native-animatable for a better user experience. We utilise drop-down menus and multi-response forms from react-native-element-dropdown to create the fields for additional information. By setting boundaries for each category of information, we are able to store the data neatly in the database, as opposed to a TextInput function. For the setting of profile pictures, we utilise Expo ImagePicker, which provides access to the system's UI for selecting images and videos from the phone's library or taking a photo with the camera.

##### **Implementation challenges** {#implementation-challenges-1}

For editing profiles, we initially wanted to allow users to change their usernames. However, we faced issues updating the data in the database as editing the username in the user node does not update the other nodes (such as chat and username nodes) in our database. Thus, other users would not be able to view the updated username from their accounts. For simplicity’s sake, we decided to disable this function.

#### **Friends List**  {#friends-list}

##### **Description** {#description-2}

As Let’sEat is designed to function as a social networking platform, Let’sEat should have a fully functional friends’ list that allows users to connect with others easily and send them meal requests. 

Through the “Add Friend” screen, users will be able to search up the usernames and/or emails of other users, and send them a friend request. Before sending them a request, users can also view other users’ profiles to ensure that they are sending the request to the correct person, or to find out more about that particular user.  
Users will also be able to view incoming friend requests. Once accepted, users will then be updated as friends in each others’ database.

Apart from users’ being able to view their friends’ profile, users can also chat with them, perhaps to confirm meeting details or locations to eat at. As with any friends list, there will also be an option to remove existing friends if the user wishes to do so.  

From the Home Page, users can set the status on whether they are available to eat via a toggle switch. On the Friends List, friends who are “available to eat” would be marked with a green dot and sorted to the top of the list. 

![][image11]  
*Home page with Toggle Switch set to Available*

##### **Implementation Philosophy** {#implementation-philosophy-2}

When adding a friend, a user can search up their friend’s username amongst existing users, stored in Firebase Realtime Database. Alternatively, the user can type their friends’ email (but their friend will only pop up when the full email address is written (no auto-complete for email-address, only usernames).

Users’ are able to view the profiles of other users, via a “View Profile” button. The button will redirect the user to the Public Profile screen (PublicProfile.tsx). Only non-sensitive data will be displayed on the user’s public profile page. 

Once a user sends a friend request, a notification will pop-up, informing the user that they have successfully sent a request. On the receiving end, the user will receive an incoming request that they can choose to accept or decline.

When accepting friend requests, the friends' list of both users is updated in the Realtime Database and the request is removed. When removing a friend, the friends’ list of both users is updated as well. Friends are also able to chat with each other, to clarify additional details about their meetup/eating plans.

Adding or removing friends also updates the friendsCount which is a counter stored under a user’s data in Realtime Database that keeps track of the user’s current number of friends, mainly for tracking achievements (elaborated further later).

The AvailabilitySlider component is responsible for managing the user's availability status. When the user interacts with the toggle switch, the component updates the isAvailable state both locally and in Firebase Realtime Database. This ensures real-time synchronization across the app, reflecting the user's current status to friends. Friends who are available to eat are sorted to the top of the list for convenience.

##### **Implementation Challenges** {#implementation-challenges-2}

Few issues were encountered whilst developing the friend’s list. One notable issue would be the fact that since users are able to send friend requests to the same user several times, it would lead to several incoming requests from the same user, leaving several unnecessary requests being left in the database and/or displayed to the user. The solution was to only render unique requests (i.e one per user), and the moment the request was accepted or denied, all other incoming requests from the same user would be removed from the database.

An example of more trivial issues encountered would be the ability to send friend requests to users that were already in the users’ friend’s list, but these issues were typically quickly solved with a pull request for bug fixes/invalid implementations.

#### **Meal Requests (“Open Jio” and “Booking”)**  {#meal-requests-(“open-jio”-and-“booking”)}

##### **Description** {#description-3}

Arguably the core feature and purpose of our application, users can send meal requests to other users and invite them to have a meal together. We have given users two options for sending meal requests: Open Jio and Booking

* Open Jio  
  * Open Jio is designed to be a spontaneous meal request, requesting for the other user to have a meal at the current time and date.   
* Booking  
  * Booking is designed to be a reservation-type system, where users can request to have a meal with someone on a designated date, at a designated time.

Users will be able to send out a single request to multiple users at once.

![][image14]![][image15]  
*Send Request Screen and Booking Details Screen*

Additionally, users can set whether they are open to receiving requests from strangers on the Profile page. Only if they are, other users (who may not be friends) that share the same characteristics (i.e. faculty, campus accommodation) will also be displayed which the user can invite.

 ![][image16]  
*Profile Page with slider to set whether they are open to strangers’ requests*

For booking requests, upon clicking on a date in the calendar, common availabilities (timings not booked) among the user and selected friends will be displayed (as “Suggested Times”) by analysing users' calendars and availability. Each booking assumes a time interval of an hour.

![][image17]

*Booking Details with Suggested Timings shown*

When requests are accepted, each user will also have a calendar that displays the users’ upcoming events. Once two users have met up and the event has passed, each user will be able to confirm that they have met for a meal. When both users have confirmed the meetup within the same day, the app will consider the meal event successful.  
![][image18]![][image19]  
*Requests Page with Calendar and Home Page with Today’s Events*

In addition, when users log into the app, there will be a login notification that informs the user of how many incoming requests they have. If they have any incoming request, they will be redirected to the requests screen.   
![][image20]![][image21]  
*Login Notification for Requests*

##### **Implementation Philosophy** {#implementation-philosophy-3}

For meal requests, users will be able to search from two types of user groups: Friends that are currently in the user’s Friends List, as well as users that share similar traits to the user. These traits are filled in by the user during the onboarding process, and can be changed at any time (under “Edit Profile” in the Profile screen). When searching, the recommendations based on faculty and campus accommodation will be dynamically updated and rendered based on the current user’s traits. To ensure that users 

Icons are also included to help users differentiate between the different meal requests. These icons are also displayed in the user’s calendar. The calendar (i.e Schedule.tsx) was implemented using react-native-calendars package, largely utilising the Agenda component. When a meal request is accepted, an event for each user (both sender and receiver) is created and stored under the ‘events’ subcollection. Supplementary features, such as the Schedule will retrieve information from the ‘events’ subcollection to display the user’s events on the calendar. Lastly, the Schedule component also has a remove button for each event. Removing the event from the Schedule will then remove the event completely from the subcollection.

Type-specific features:

* Open Jio  
  * When sending an Open Jio request to a particular user, the time and date of the event is recorded as the time and date that the request was sent (using currentDate.now())   
  * Given that Open Jio is meant to be a spontaneous request, users are not allowed to have duplicate Open Jio events with the same user on the same day.  
* Booking  
  * When selecting time and date for a Booking request, users are not allowed to select a time and date in the past.   
  * Time and date selection implemented using react-native-datetimepicker package.

As mentioned in the description, meal requests have a confirmation system to ensure that both users have met on the day itself. This confirmation option will only be possible via the ‘Today’s Events’ component on the Home Page. The component only displays the user’s events on the current day. Once both users confirm that they have met, the event will be removed from both users’ ‘events’ subcollection, possible via a sharedEventID. The event will be considered successful and relevant counters will be updated (see Gamification section under Features).

Additionally, users will be able to set their preference as to whether they wish to be open to invitations from strangers (i.e. users that are not currently on their friendsList). The default setting is ‘open’, however, via a slider in the user’s profile page, the user can choose to avoid eating requests from strangers by not appearing under other users’ recommended selection of users when sending out eating requests

![][image22]![][image23]  
*Slider for users that are non-friends (under Profile Screen)*

The "Suggested Times" feature aims to enhance user convenience by identifying optimal time slots for group activities based on the availability of all participants, thereby streamlining the process of scheduling group events. The fetchEvents function retrieves events from Firebase for both the current user and their selected friends, and stores them in an events object. We filter out events of type "Booking". The parseEventDate function then converts event date and time strings into JavaScript Date objects, ensuring the selected date and event dates in the database can be compared accurately. An IntervalTree data structure is built by inserting each event's time interval (assuming one hour) into the tree, and this data structure efficiently manages and queries time intervals. The intervalTree.search method is used to find all busy intervals that overlap with the full day interval (from 00:00 to 23:59 on the selected date), then iterates through these busy intervals to find gaps between them, which represent free time slots. Any remaining time at the end of the day is also considered a free slot. The freeSlots array, containing all the identified free intervals, is set as the suggested times for booking.

##### **Implementation Challenges** {#implementation-challenges-3}

Several challenges were encountered when implementing the meal request system. In our initial prototype, once users accepted meal requests, the event would be directly stored in both users’ agenda. However, we soon realised that given the inflexible nature of the react-native-calendars package, it was difficult to extract the data once stored in the Agenda component. For instance, it was difficult to sort Booking events in the calendar by time, because the package naturally sorts based on order of entry.

To afford greater flexibility, we decided to store events in an ‘events’ subcollection, thereafter utilising the data within to implement supplementary features. This enabled us to sort agenda entries by time, and also made our code more future-proof. 

Another challenge was encountered when implementing the confirmation system. Initially, when requests were accepted, two unique events would be created, one for the sender and one for the receiver. However, when a user confirmed the event, it would be difficult to find the corresponding event in the sender’s database. Hence, adding a sharedEventID by concatenating user ID strings and timestamps enabled us to identify corresponding events swiftly.

Initially, the IntervalTree did not account for some busy intervals as we did not sort the busy intervals by start time, causing inaccuracies in identifying gaps between them during iteration. After sorting, we can then efficiently find and list the free time slots by checking the end of one interval against the start of the next, maintaining chronological order.

#### **Takeaway Request**  {#takeaway-request}

##### **Description** {#description-4}

On some days, students may not be able to properly meet up to have a meal, due to their busy schedules. Hence, they may wish to request for someone to take-away food for them. To address this, we have also included a takeaway option under our requests section. For now, users can ask any of their friends to help them take-away food. ##### **Implementation Philosophy** {#implementation-philosophy-4}

Given that takeaway requests are typically spontaneous, the takeaway event is created on the current date when the request is accepted.

We also chose eatery locations to be predetermined rather than a TextInput for future extensibility, and achievement tracking.

###### Location Services {#location-services}

Additionally, the map tracks the location of nearby users (within 2km radius). Users can view nearby users’ profiles and request meals. They would be able to see the distance away. Users can also share their location with others by generating a Google Maps URL using the latitude and longitude of the user's location. When a user clicks the "Share Location" button, the app will export a link that can be shared or opened in a web browser. 

**![][image30]**  
*Nearby Users Screen*

##### **Implementation Philosophy** {#implementation-philosophy-5}

The map component largely relies on the react-native-maps package. The initial coordinates and zoom of the map were obtained via checking on Google Maps to ensure that the initial screen displays the entirety of NUS. To future-proof the code, information about each and every eatery is stored in an eateries.json file that can be easily updated with more eateries in the future. 

Reviews for each eatery are stored in the Realtime Database in the ‘eateries’ subcollection, with each eatery being numbered with a unique id.

Location tracking for users was implemented with Expo Location by calling Location.getCurrentPositionAsync. This function requests for one-time delivery of the user's current location and marks it on the map. Users’ location details are stored in Firebase Realtime Database and called in the NearbyUsersScreen component. Location sharing is implemented via the React Native Share API, which allows sharing content from our app to other apps. The link format https://www.google.com/maps/search/?api=1\&query=${location?.latitude},${location?.longitude} is used to create a searchable map link that will open in Google Maps with the user's location.

In the future, we are looking to allow Background Location tracking for greater convenience when using the app.

##### **Implementation Challenges** {#implementation-challenges-5}

In line with the challenge alongside takeaway requests, information of eateries had to be manually input. We tried to display Google Maps, however the map provider does not seem to work on Expo App anymore. Hence, we settled with the default map view. Location.getCurrentPositionAsync also takes some time to resolve, so we are looking to improve it by lowering accuracy.

#### **Gamification**  {#gamification}

##### **Description** {#description-6}

To encourage users to continue using the app, and to utilise the app as a social networking tool, various forms of gamification have been added (in the form of streaks, achievements and leaderboards) to incentivise users to have more meals with their friends.

* Streaks  
  * Similar to existing social media applications (e.g SnapChat, BeReal), LetsEat has also implemented a streak functionality between users. Upon any successful meal or takeaway request (after confirmation), the streak between two users will increase (displayed in the home page). Streaks will eventually reset if there is no activity between users for more than a week. Streaks are also “time-gated”, to prevent users from continuously faking appointments to increase their streak count.  
* Achievements  
  * Various achievements are achievable within the application, such as having a certain number of meal requests, friends, takeaways, or even planning events. These achievements can be viewed on the user’s profile page.  
* Leaderboards  
  * To add an element of competitiveness to the application as a form of encouragement, users with the most number of successfully completed meals will be displayed on the leaderboard for all users to see. More categories can easily be added in the future.  
* EXP/Levelling System  
  * To further incentivise users to continue using our application, a levelling system provides a sense of achievement and progress. It encourages continuous engagement as users work towards higher levels, unlocking rewards or features, and it enhances user retention by making the experience more engaging and rewarding.

![][image31]![][image32]  
*Streaks and Leaderboard (Home) and Achievements (under Profile)*  
*![][image33]*  
*Levelling display with EXP Progress Bar (under Profile)*

##### **Implementation Philosophy** {#implementation-philosophy-6}

In order to “time-gate” streaks, if a user has already had a successful event with another user within the same day, any other successful event within the same day will not increment streak count (resets at 12 AM SGT). If two users do not interact with each other for more than a week, the streak resets. To view the remaining amount of time before reset, users can tap on the user that they have a streak with to view the remaining time.

For achievements, every user has a counter for various categories of achievements

* mealsCount: Tracks number of successful meals  
* takeawayCount: Tracks number of successful takeaways  
* friendsCount: Tracks number of friends  
* plannerCount: Tracks number of successful meals where the current user is the sender

With more achievements being added in the future, more counters can be simply implemented.

Similarly, implementing the leaderboards was also relatively simple, as it is mainly tracking all users’ mealsCount and displaying the top few.

For our levelling system, users are currently able to gain levels and experience points via two main ways. Leaving a review at an eatery grants \+50 XP, whilst having a successful meal with a friend (via the confirmation system) grants \+100 XP. The XP that is required to level up increments as the users’ level increases, in an attempt to “time-gate” the user’s progress such that they develop a sense of achievement through their usage of the app over time.

##### **Implementation Challenges** {#implementation-challenges-6}

When implementing streaks, we noticed that the difference in time zone was an issue if we wanted the “time-gate” to reset at 12AM (GMT \+8). Thus, we had to implement some conversion to ensure that the feature was functioning optimally.

**Possible Extensions**  
Users' profiles will be assigned various achievement tiers based on their level. Those who reach higher tiers will appear more credible or popular on their public profile page, making them more likely to attract requests from strangers or acquaintances for a meal.

##### **Possible Business Venture** {#possible-business-venture}

Given that LetsEat is targeted at NUS students and plans to be a completely free application, we have developed a potential means to generate funds and encourage users to use the app by handing out meal vouchers or discounts.

* In collaboration with NUS eateries, to confirm that users have actually met at the eatery for their meal, users will have to scan the QR code on their receipt to indicate successful meal completion and earn points.  
* Points can be used to redeem rewards such as restaurant / canteen vouchers.

Observing the relationships between entities via an ERD allows us to identify issues with data consistency. Redundant data may be stored across different documents or collections. An ERD allows us to easily deal with data duplication, ensuring consistency throughout our database.

### **Software Engineering Practices** {#software-engineering-practices}

#### **Version Control** {#version-control}

**Branching**  
**![][image36]**

We utilize Git for version control to manage our codebase efficiently. The remote main branch consistently contains a stable version of the code. When developing new features, we pull from the main branch and create a separate feature branch named using the feature-developer convention. This approach ensures that work on different features remains isolated, preventing code contamination and simplifying debugging. Once a feature is complete, we commit the changes to the feature branch and initiate a pull request to merge the updates into the main branch.

**Pull Requests**  
**![][image37]**

We use Git's pull request feature to update the remote main branch. The developer who worked on the feature creates a pull request and assigns the partner as the code reviewer. This process ensures communication and prevents incorrect handling of merge conflicts, which can lead to bugs. The pull request is only completed after the code has been reviewed, approved, and any merge conflicts have been resolved.

#### **Git Issues** {#git-issues}

![][image38]  
We used Git Issues to monitor open issues or bugs within the app. Tags were applied to categorize the type of issue, such as fixes or potential enhancements. An issue would only be closed once the problem had been resolved.

#### **Frequent Code Refactoring** {#frequent-code-refactoring}

As part of maintaining and improving the quality of our app, we practice frequent code refactoring. This ensures that our codebase remains clean, efficient, and easy to maintain. Common issues include duplicated code, long methods, large classes, and overly complex logic. Refactoring in small, manageable increments minimizes risk and each change is thoroughly tested to ensure it does not affect the existing functionality. Aspects of code refactoring adopted include naming convention, where we ensure that all variables, functions, and classes follow a consistent and meaningful naming convention. This makes the code more readable and easier to understand. For example, we use camelCase for variable names and PascalCase for class names in our codebase.

#### **Code Reusability** {#code-reusability}

By utilizing componetization and leveraging existing libraries, we ensure that our app is scalable, easy to extend, and maintain. This results in higher code quality, greater reliability, and a more efficient development process.

##### **Componentization** {#componentization}

Modular Design: We design our app using a modular approach, breaking down the application into smaller, self-contained components. Each component encapsulates specific functionality and can be developed, tested, and maintained independently. For example, we have separate components for user authentication, meal booking requests and eatery details. This allows us to update or extend each part without affecting the others.

Reusable Components: Components are designed to be reusable across different parts of the app. For instance, a send / accept request component used in “open jio” can also be used in other features like “booking” and “takeaway”. We ensure that components are loosely coupled and highly cohesive, which makes them easy to integrate and reuse.

Scalability and Extension: By componentizing our application, we ensure that it can scale easily. New features can be added by simply integrating new components or extending existing ones.

##### **Libraries** {#libraries}

For complex components and features, we leverage existing libraries that are well-maintained and widely used. This approach saves development time and ensures we use reliable, tested solutions. Libraries such as React for building user interfaces are integral parts of our tech stack. By using established libraries, we benefit from the collective expertise of the community, which leads to higher code quality and greater reliability. These libraries often come with extensive documentation and community support, which helps in quickly resolving issues and implementing best practices.

#### **Logging** {#logging}

We use logging to identify and diagnose errors. When an error occurs, logs provide detailed information about the execution flow of the app, making it easier to understand the root cause. By logging errors using console.log(), we are able to anticipate, detect, and manage exceptions that may occur during the execution of a function. This improves the reliability, robustness, and maintainability of the application. 

![][image39]

#### **Security Measures** {#security-measures}

To secure access to our API, Firebase Authentication, and Firebase Realtime Database, we keep private keys and tokens hidden in a .env file. This file is stored locally in the developer's repository, ensuring that sensitive information is not publicly available in our source code.

### **Quality Control** {#quality-control}

#### **Unit Testing** {#unit-testing}

Unit Testing refers to the testing of individual components of systems, including methods, classes and sub-systems, to ensure their correctness, functionality and reliability. Unit tests help enhance code quality by enforcing well-defined behaviours and ensuring that units perform their intended functions accurately. This serves as documentation and specifications for expected code behaviour. By thoroughly testing individual units, we can build a robust foundation for the app, thereby minimizing the risk of critical bugs or issues down the line.

#### **User Testing** {#user-testing}

User testing was conducted with end users from our target audience group. This is crucial as it provides invaluable insights into the user experience and helps identify potential areas for improvement. We utilised Donald A. Norman’s seven fundamental design principles to test and understand how users interact with the app. 

1. Discoverability: Allows the user to understand where to perform actions.  
2. Conceptual Models: Simple explanations of how something works.  
3. Affordance: Perceived properties of an object.  
4. Mappings: Relationships between the controls and their effects.  
5. Signifiers: Tells the user where to perform an action.  
6. Constraints: Restricts possible interactions.  
7. Feedback: Communicates the response to a user’s action.

### **Limitations & Challenges** {#limitations-&-challenges}

#### **Third-Party API Restrictions** {#third-party-api-restrictions}

Third-party libraries often come with their own set of feature and customization options. While we use them for convenience sake, it limits our ability to fully customize the functionality to fit our application’s needs in the future. Additionally, dependency and compatibility issues may arise if the library is not maintained or has a bug, impacting our app’s performance.

##### 

#### **Storage and Data Limits** {#storage-and-data-limits}

The free-tier Firebase Realtime Database and Firebase Storage come with specific limits on storage and data usage. Realtime Database restricts the number of documents, data storage, and data transfer per month, while Firebase Storage imposes limits on storage space and bandwidth. If our app exceeds these limits, it could affect the app's availability and performance.

However, considering the current scale of the application, it is unlikely that these availability and performance limits will be reached. Therefore, users should not expect significant downtime due to the overuse of cloud resources.

#### **Lack of Resources on Testing** {#lack-of-resources-on-testing}

Although there were numerous challenges during the testing phase, the most significant obstacle was the scarcity of online materials and resources on user testing. Many resources explained the different types of testing and their advantages but lacked guidance on how to conduct them.

1. React Native and TypeScript (cross-platform mobile app development)   
2. Firebase (account authentication and backend service)   
3. Expo (navigation)  
4. Git and Github (version control, issue tracking)
